<Article
  title="Core Communication Principles That Work in Any Co-op Game"
  description="Most team wipes are communication failures, not mechanical ones. These habits will make you dramatically better at any co-op game you play with friends or strangers."
  kicker="Teamwork"
  date="2026-06-24"
  heading="Co-op Communication Principles"
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="sec">
    <p>The difference between a smooth crew and a group that wipes three times in a row is rarely raw skill. It’s almost always information flow. The good news: communication skills transfer across almost every co-op game.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>1. Call intent, not just observation</h2>
    <p>“I see a monster” is weak. “Bracken behind me, moving toward the door, I’m backing up” is strong. Good calls include what you see + what you are doing about it + what you need from others.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>2. Establish a shared vocabulary before the run</h2>
    <p>Decide on short names for common situations (“bracken”, “coil”, “pop”, “hug”). Don’t invent new slang mid-run when people are stressed. One 2-minute conversation before the first mission saves a lot of “wait what did you mean?” deaths.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>3. Use timing and priority language</h2>
    <p>“We have 90 seconds left” is more useful than “hurry”. “I can finish this one objective then I’m out” tells the team whether they should wait or leave without you.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>4. Accept that someone will be the designated “bad call” person</h2>
    <p>In every good crew there is usually one person willing to say “this is not worth it, we’re leaving” even when there is still loot on the table. Rotate the role so nobody becomes the permanent buzzkill.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>5. Debrief briefly after wipes</h2>
    <p>30 seconds of “what actually killed us?” after a bad run prevents the same mistake happening four runs in a row. Most groups just queue again and repeat the exact same error.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec next">
    <p>These principles are deliberately game-agnostic. They apply whether you’re playing Goose Goose Duck, Lethal Company, or any other co-op title. The specific monsters and maps change — the communication failures are remarkably consistent.</p>
  </section>
</Article>
